Numerical integration

To perform numerical integration of a one-dimensional function, we can use the integrate function.

For example, we can compute \(\int_{2}^5 x^2 + \cos(x) dx\) as follows

f <- function(x) {
   return(x ^ 2 + cos(x))
}
integrate(f, lower = 2, upper = 5)
## 37.13178 with absolute error < 4.1e-13

The function integrate accepts the following parameters:

  • f the function to integrate, must accept a numerical vector and return a numerical vector of the same length;
  • lower and upper are the lower and upper limits of integration, respectively, they can be -Inf or Inf
  • there are further optional parameters, cf.?integrate

It is a requirement that the function f accepts a numerical vector and returns a numerical vector of the same length. For example, the following fails

f <- function() {
   return(1)
}
integrate(f, lower  = 0, upper = 1)
## Error in f(x, ...): unused argument (x)
  1. Describe the problem in above code chunk.

integrate expects a function as first argument that takes a vector as input and outputs a vector of function evaluations. In above code chunk, the function f does not accept any argument.

Also, the following fails because the function f does not return a vector

f <- function(x) {
   return(1)
}
integrate(f, lower  = 0, upper = 1)
## Error in integrate(f, lower = 0, upper = 1): evaluation of function gave a result of wrong length

To make the example work, we can change the example as follows

f <- function(x) {
   return(rep(1, length(x)))
}
integrate(f, lower  = 0, upper = 1)
## 1 with absolute error < 1.1e-14

Instead, we could have used the function Vectorize to vectorize the original function definition; for example

g <- function(x) {
   return(1)
}

g_vect <- Vectorize(g)

integrate(g_vect, lower = 0, upper = 1)
## 1 with absolute error < 1.1e-14

## 32 with absolute error < 0.0015
verify <- function(d) {
   integral <- integrate(d, lower = -Inf, upper = +Inf)
   # absolute value of d
   d_abs <- function(x) abs(d(x))
   integral_abs <- integrate(d_abs, lower = -Inf, upper = +Inf)
   if (abs(integral$value - 1) < 1e-6 &&
       abs(integral$value - integral_abs$value) < 1e-6)
      return("ok")
   else
      return("not ok")
}

verify(dnorm)
## [1] "ok"
verify(function(x) dnorm(x, mean = 10, sd = 10))
## [1] "ok"
verify(function(x) dnorm(x, mean = -10, sd = .5))
## [1] "ok"
verify(function(x) dgamma(x, shape = 1))
## [1] "ok"
verify(function(x) dgamma(x, shape = 5))
## [1] "ok"
verify(function(x) dexp(x))
## [1] "ok"
verify(function(x) dexp(x, rate = 10))
## [1] "ok"
# not a density
verify(function(x) dnorm(x)^2)
## [1] "not ok"
dsin_raw <- function(x) {
   if (x > 0 && x < pi) {
      return(sin(x))
   } else{
      return(0)
   }
}

dsin_raw <- function(x) {
   if (x > 0 && x < pi) {
      return(sin(x))
   } else{
      return(0)
   }
}


# not ok, as it does not integrate to 1
verify(Vectorize(dsin_raw))
## [1] "not ok"
# normalise dsin accordingly
n <- integrate(Vectorize(dsin_raw), lower = -Inf, upper = +Inf)$value
dsin <- function(x) {
   return(Vectorize(dsin_raw)(x) / n)
}
verify(dsin)
## [1] "ok"

Expectations of random variables

We can use numerical integration to compute the expected value of random variables and of functions of random variables (using the rule of the lazy statistician).

For example, we can obtain the expected value of \(X^2 + \sin(X)\) where \(X \sim N(3,.5^2)\) as follows

m = 3
s = 0.5
xf <- function(x) {
   return((x ^ 2 + sin(x)) * dnorm(x, mean = m, sd = s))
}
integrate(xf, lower = -Inf, upper = Inf)
## 9.374538 with absolute error < 6.5e-06

Variance

We can obtain the variance of a random variable using the formula \[ \mathbb{V}(X) = \mathbb{E}(X^2) - \mathbb{E}(X)^2\]

We can, for example, obtain the variance of a Gaussian random variable \(X \sim N(3, 4^2)\) as

f <- function(x) {
   return(dnorm(x, mean = 3, sd = 4))
}
xf <- function(x) {
   return(x * f(x))
}
xxf <- function(x) {
   return(x ^ 2 * f(x))
}
var_x <- integrate(xxf, lower = -Inf, upper = Inf)$value -
   integrate(xf, lower = -Inf, upper = Inf)$value ^ 2
var_x 
## [1] 16
  1. Write a generic function that takes as input the density function and returns the variance.
  2. Obtain the variance of \(Y= \sin(X)\) where \(X \sim Beta(\mathrm{shape1} = 5,\ \mathrm{shape2} = 4)\).
dvar <- function(d, trafo = function(x) x) {
    E_x_square <- integrate(function(x) trafo(x)^2 * d(x),
                            lower = -Inf,
                            upper = Inf)$value
    E_x <- integrate(function(x) trafo(x) * d(x),
                     lower = -Inf,
                     upper = Inf)$value
   return(E_x_square - E_x^2)
}

dvar(function(x) dnorm(x, sd = 1))
## [1] 1
dvar(function(x) dnorm(x, sd = sqrt(42)))
## [1] 42
dvar(function(x) dbeta(x, shape1 = 5, shape2 = 4),
     function(x) sin(x))
## [1] 0.01773525

Empirical mean

To compute the empirical mean \(\bar{x} = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^n x_i}{n}\) we use the mean function. It computes the arithmetic mean of a vector.

x_obs <- runif(100, min = 0, max = 10)
mean(x_obs)
## [1] 5.098399

We can also exclude NA values with the na.rm = TRUE argument,

obs <- c(13, 0.5, NA, 34, 9, NA)
mean(obs, na.rm = TRUE)
## [1] 14.125
  1. Visually compare the empirical mean and the true mean of a Gaussian random variable for different values of the variance parameter and for an increasing number of observations (e.g.\(n = 10,100,1000, 5000, 10000\)).
  2. Sample \(n=100\) i.i.d. observations from an exponential distribution with \(\lambda = 1\) (rate) and compute the empirical mean. Repeat the experiment 100 times and record the 100 computed empirical means.
compare <- function(variance) {
   empirical_mean <- function(n) mean(rnorm(n, sd = sqrt(variance)))
   n <- c(10, 100, 1000, 5000, 10000, 50000)
   plot(n, sapply(n, empirical_mean))
   abline(h = 0)
}

compare(100)

compare(1)

compare(.01)

# empirical mean of 100 iid obervations
empirical <- function() mean(rexp(100, rate = 1))
# repetitions
empirical_means <- replicate(100, empirical())
# observe how the empirical means fluctuate
# around the expected value of 1
plot(empirical_means)

Empirical variance and standard deviation

The empirical variance \(s^2 = \sum_{i=1}^n (\bar{x} - x_i)^2 / (n-1)\) can be obtained using the var function that takes as input a vector of observations.

sample <- rnorm(100)
var(sample)
## [1] 1.051393

As for the mean function, we can exclude NA values,

var(c(3, 2, 12, 4, NA, 54), na.rm = TRUE)
## [1] 491

var(X_obs)

normalize <- function(x) {
   return((x - mean(x)) / sd(x))
}

Y_obs_normalized <- normalize(Y_obs)
mean(Y_obs_normalized)
## [1] -1.776357e-17

## [1] 1
  1. data.frame of \(100\) observations (rows), of \(100\) Gaussian random variables (columns) with mean \(1\)
df <- data.frame(
   matrix(rnorm(100 * 100, mean = 1),
          nrow = 100))

The empirical means and variances for each variable

empirical_means <- colMeans(df)
empirical_vars <- apply(df, 2, var)

The standard errors of the mean for each of the 100 variables can be obtained as follows

sem <- sqrt(empirical_vars / 100)

The standard deviation of the 100 empirical means is

sd_of_means <- sd(empirical_means)

We compare by plotting a constant line for the sd_of_means and plotting sems

plot(sem)
abline(h = sd_of_means)
